-   Git tracks and saves your progress through a project so that you    
    might update and edit projects


- Git Basic Commands:

    1. $ git init 
        - Initialize local git repository

    2. $ git add <file>
        - Add File(s) to Index

    3. $ git status 
        - Check Status of Working Tree

    4. $ git commit
        - Commit Changes in Index

    5. $ git push 
        - Push to Remote repository

    6. $ git pull 
        - Pull latest from remote repository

    7. $ git clone
        - Pulls and clones into a new directory

    8. $ git rm -- cached <file>
        - Removes a file from staging area/ repository

    9. $ git add .
        - Adds all files into staging area

    10. $ git touch <index.html>
        - Adds a file with the file name after
    


- Commiting Files and Changes:

    1. $ git commit
        - This will open a 'vim editor'

    2. Press i 
        - Allowing you to type

    3. Uncomment 'Initial Commit'
        - Allows for first interior comment 

    4. 'Esc'
        - Takes you out of insert mode

    5. ':wq'
        - Finalizes commit

    B. Faster Method:
        1. $ git commit -m 'Changed "___"'
            - Changes the master (-m)
            - Adds a comment in the parenthesis at the end